Using NETCONF over the Simple Object
Access Protocol (SOAP)
2006", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC4743.html", target="_top", tooltip="The Network Configuration Protocol (NETCONF) is applicable to a wide range of devices in a variety of environments.  Web Services is one such environment and is presently characterized by the use of the Simple Object Access Protocol (SOAP).  NETCONF finds many benefits in this environment: from the reuse of existing standards, to ease of software development, to integration with deployed systems.  Herein, we describe SOAP over HTTP and SOAP over Blocks Exchange Extensible Protocol (BEEP) bindings for NETCONF. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  cites -> RFC4743;
  RFC4741 [label="RFC4741
NETCONF Configuration Protocol
2006", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC4741.html", target="_top", tooltip="The Network Configuration Protocol (NETCONF) defined in this document provides mechanisms to install, manipulate, and delete the configuration of network devices.  It uses an Extensible Markup Language (XML)-based data encoding for the configuration data as well as the protocol messages.  The NETCONF protocol operations are realized on top of a simple Remote Procedure Call (RPC) layer. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  cites -> RFC4741;
